text: Heres my 2 guesses at what happened here.Â   1st guess:Â  Jason's character was popular in school, but Gordom, not so much (that is pretty obvious from the trailer).Â  Jason' characterÂ was involved with some prank that was going to be played on Gordo, but the prank went to far, without Jason's character knowing this.Â  So Jason's character thinks Gordo is being a bit silly for holding on toÂ a grudge for so long.Â  When Jason's character sees the video of what actuallyÂ happened due to the prank, that is why he reacts so emotionally.Â  He did not know the complete outcome until that time.Â   2nd guess:Â  Jason's character was part of the group in high school that bullied Gordo.Â  This had a lasting affect on Gordo.Â He may have already had some mental issues, and the memories of the bullying just exasperated them.Â  He is seeking revenge on each of the participants ofÂ his bullying.Â  The video Jason's character is watching is either showing some of what Gordo has done to the others, or it is showing something happening to Jason's character's wife at the hands of Gordo.

text: I absolutely LOVED this film!  Saw it in the theater, twice in one week!  I admired how this movie didn't rely on endless blood or unnecessary stabbing to install horror in the story.  Instead, it used manipulation to not only play mind games with the characters, but the audience as well.  The cast was excellent, also.  I'd actually never heard of Joel Edgerton before seeing this; but after leaving the theater, I look forward to his next films.  On an unrelated note, his eyes and cheekbones made me think of a younger, bearded Conan O'Brien (another media figure on my watch list).

text: Just saw the movie finally and it was really good. Good cinematography, clever dialogue that is used in a way of foreshadowing, and while seemingly simplistic in plot by watching the trailer it was actually quite unique in how everything unfolded. New director too so I'm looking forward to what else comes out from him.  One thing that is annoying though, which is not the movie's fault, is that by watching the trailer not only does it come across as a completely different movie, it actually spoils a lot of things. This is not a typical "crazy stalker revenge flick" that has been overused in so many movies as this trailer comes across.  Also the two jump scares this movie had were so well done! Literally everyone in the theatre screamed, it was amazing.. lol

text: The Gift is one of those films that does exactly what it says on the tin. Present the audience with a jigsaw puzzle and leaves us to fill in the gaps. Quite a few questions spring to mind such as; 1)How much trouble was the Callum marraige in to begin with?  2)Whether she identifies heavily with Gordon Mosely because she was bullied herself or not, Why would Robyn Callum trust a complete stranger over her own husband? 3)Do people ever truly change after high school/college or not. If so, is it for the better or worse? 4)Would Simons phobia of Monkeys and hatred of his own father suggest that he was sexually abused himself? 5)How long were the Callums married before all this? 6)Do you truly know the person you married? 7)Although the answers pretty clear for some, when Simon shoved and pinned him to the floor, why did Gordo for a military man not fight back? 8)Is the idea of an heinous act more powerful than the deed itself? 9)Is the baby Simons or Gordo's? 10)How fitting was Simon for the manner Gordo took his revenge?

text: MY RATING - 7 out of 10  The Gift is an intelligent physiological thriller that starts out in the vein of films like Arlington Road or Single White Female and then takes an unexpected turn that makes the viewer really question their loyalties. Joel Edgerton is the writer & director and he also plays Gordo in this , the so called bad guy and he does really good job. Jason Bateman and Rebecca Hall are good too as the couple who move into a new house in California only to find an old friend hanging around more than they would like. I enjoyed this because it has you guessing the characters motives throughout and it had a real edge of the seat feel about it .

text: Exceptional, dark, gritty and i would even say Hitchcockian thriller. It is simple, but nevertheless intriguing and unnerving concept that will appeal to all generations. Kids can learn from it, adults and by that i mean those who found themselves in these characters should think for a moment and probably feel remorse. Cast is top notch with Edgerton and Bateman having good chemistry plus Hall does a good work here. Atmosphere is very creepy and eerie at times and you can feel your hart pounding in those haunting, uncanny moments. All in all it is a strong well directed film with well written script and the message which should not be forgotten after experiencing it. GO SEE IT.

text: This movie was good except how it made oddballs/victims of bullying look. I was bullied for nine years for being different and "the quiet kid" but i'd never hurt anyone, how would that make me a better person than them anyway? I've never even been bullied after that or treated badly by anyone i've met, I just ended up in a class full of insecure morons in the school I went to for just those first 9 school years. And I saw other odd kids get bullied there too who ended up with friends in the future away from that school and those kids would probably never hurt anyone either, they just moved on like me and made a better life for themselves. Odd does not equal a freak who will shoot up a school or rape someones wife for revenge but at least the movie came through with its message to not bully... And it was very exciting although the ending gave me the chills and made me feel a little bit sick.
